The results showed that the Phos intensity of CD@SiO2 remained stable in different environments, and its variation range is small. The specific changes are as follows: (1) The Phos intensity remained unchanged or decreased slightly under near-neutral and alkaline conditions (pH: 5.0–11.0) but dropped significantly in acidic conditions (pH: 3.0–4.0). (2) The presence of atmosphere could reduce the Phos intensity slightly, and the effect of O2 is stronger than that of N2. (3) With the prolongation of UV radiation time, the Phos intensity first decreased slowly (0–1 h), and then increased slowly (1–4 h). (4) Low (<0 ℃) and high temperature (>50 ℃) reduced the Phos intensity slightly (
                           Figure S4
                        ). Compared to other phosphorescence materials, this materials have high stability in various ambient conditions, which is suitable for different application scenarios [33,38–40].

The luminescence fitting curve (red line) of CD@SiO2 showed that the photoluminescent lifetime was found to be up to 1.20 s (Em = 530 nm), and their phosphorescence decay included two components of 0.22 s (12.54 %) and 1.34 s (87.46 %) with an average of 1100.19 ms (Fig. 4B, 4C, 
                           Table S1-S2
                        ).
